results.description: The bat fauna of Africa and surrounding islands boasts more than 300 species, but the distributions of many species are poorly known. Despite the crucial role of bats (Chiroptera) as pollinators and seed dispersers of plants as well as predators of insects, one-fifth of Africa's bat species are threatened, and populations are declining due to habitat loss, disturbance and destruction of roost sites, hunting for bushmeat, land use, and pesticides. AfriBats seeks to mobilize both amateur and professional knowledge through the iNaturalist platform. These data will be used for scientific projects and informed conservation actions, which require robust data on the distributions of bat species.
results.title: AfriBats

How do animals exist in and exploit urban areas and human created resources? We welcome all observations of animals in highly human-dominated landscapes, especially those where an animal has adapted to use a human created resource (e.g. birds nesting in buildings, racoons dumpster diving, or snakes sunning themselves on the road.) Please be descriptive of the observed behaviour and include pictures where possible.

Bring us your pigeons, your house mice, your back alley coyotes!

results.description: In an effort to increase awareness of the 'lesser-studied' terrestrial arthropods, here is a repository for all sightings of Arachnids (spiders, scorpions, harvestmen, vinegaroons, etc.) and Myriapods (Centipedes, Millipedes, and allies) in North America (Mexico included). Please limit observations to the Arachnida and Myriapoda (Chilopoda, Diplopoda, Pauropoda, or Symphyla). This is not a place for insects, crustaceans, earthworms, or molluscs. As a general rule of thumb, if it has more than 8 legs, it's a go! What is the purpose of this project? Simply to learn more about the distribution and biology of secretive, obscure, bizarre, and poorly known groups of invertebrates.
results.title: Arachnids and Myriapods of North America

results.description: This is part of a larger project organized by the University of Texas' Biodiversity Collections (https://integrativebio.utexas.edu/biodiversity-collections) and funded by the University of Texas' Green Fee program starting in 2015. The iNaturalist component aims to compile biodiversity  photo observations from the Waller Creek drainage especially in the riparian corridor on and near the University of Texas campus. However, observations from anywhere within the Waller Creek drainage from any time are encouraged as well. We will also organize bioblitz events during which we invite the public, including college students and grade school students to work alongside UT Ichthyologists, Herpetologists, Entomologists and Botanists to document via photographs and specimens what's living in the drainage.

Please do not trespass on private land, and only submit observations that were legally obtained.

results.description:
Participate with Seattle in the nationwide City Nature Challenge in 2017. Cities from around the country will be cataloging their biodiversity April 14 - 18, 2017. Let's show the rest of the country how diverse our city is!

During the City Nature Challenge, you can view the Leaderboard here: https://www.nhm.org/nature/citizen-science/city-nature-challenge-2017-leaderboard

The City Nature Challange is organized by Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County and California Academy of Sciences
results.title: City Nature Challenge 2017: Seattle

results.description: Help the Seattle Metropolitan Area (including Everett, Seattle, Bellevue, Tacoma and any place within Snohomish, King and Pierce counties!) show the world how biodiverse our region is by making as many observations of as many species as possible April 27-30! You can also help with IDs for other people's observations to increase our species count, come to a bioblitz, or even hold your own event! Which city on Earth has the most nature and the most engaged residents? The City Nature Challenge 2018 (April 27-30) will help us find out! More than 70 cities on six continents are asking residents of and visitors to these urban areas to explore nature all around them and document the species they find - see the full list of cities at City Nature Challenge . Results will be announced Friday, May 4, so be sure to upload your observations by then! Building on the success of the first City Nature Challenge in 2016 between San Francisco and Los Angeles, and the 2017 City Nature Challenge across 16 US cities, the event founders, the California Academy of Sciences and the Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County, have expanded the event around the world. During the 2017 City Nature Challenge, over 126,000 observations were logged in 5 days by over 4000 citizen scientists, representing more than 8500 species in the United States! In Seattle, 1555 observations were logged by 72 people, representing 425 species! What will we find this year in the Seattle area? And what will we all find when we look all over the world? Check back here for events happening in the Seattle metropolitan area during the City Nature Challenge - join with others to make iNaturalist observations and to help ID!
results.title: City Nature Challenge 2018: Seattle Metropolitan Area

results.description:
Crows In Vermont grew out of the public's interest in the winter flocks of crows that form at day break especially in urban areas. We'll endeavor to track and map them here.

A couple of observations we are particularly interested in are: 

Count: individual or small group sightings are welcome, we encourage participants to try to estimate the size of roosting flocks. Here's a great tutorial to help: http://bit.ly/counting_eBird 

Direction of Flight AM/PM: This is the dawn or dusk movement of crows away from or to a roost site. They appear as if there is a crow highway streaming overhead. It would be fascinating to see if these streams come from multiple directions to an individual roosting site. To enter a count when you encounter streaming crows, here's a great tutorial on moving flocks: http://bit.ly/counting201_eBird

Communal Roost Site: A murder in birding terms is a flock of crows and in the winter large murders form as crows gather to roost for the night. There are many theories about why crows sleep together communally in roosts including, convenience, safety, communication and food proximity. There is some research that notes that more urban roost sites may be developing So, in a rural state like Vermont we'd like to see if we can find both urban and rural roost sites. PLEASE DO YOUR BEST TO ESTIMATE THE NUMBER OF BIRDS, see above under Count.
       
Finally, we are excited to connect people through their fascination with crows and see what we can learn together!

Many thanks to Hilary Hess, Edward Shepard and Nate Orshan who helped me pull this interest of winter crows together into a citizen science project!
results.title: Crows In Vermont

We encourage the responsible use of the iNaturalist platform. Please consider the following rules of etiquette when you are in the field:

• do not trespass on private property without landowner permission 
• communicate with land owners and managers about your activities 
• be a model for ethical wildlife watching behavior. For more detailed guidelines, visit the American Birding Association's Code of Birding Ethics at http://www.aba.org/about/ethics.html

results.description: Step into Charles Darwin’s shoes from the comfort of your own computer. Darwin for a Day is a web application that allows you to explore the Galapagos Islands through Google Street View and document its unique plants and animals. When you see an animal or plant you’d like to catalogue, you can describe it by creating an observation. You can just enter your best guess at what it is (i.e. “bird”) or enter in the scientific name, if you know it! All of your observations will be shared with the iNaturalist community & the Charles Darwin Foundation, and will contribute to research of the Galapagos Islands.

results.description:
Join us in our backyard, Golden Gate Park, for a grassroots, smartphone-powered bioblitz to catalogue every living species we can identify from the end of the panhandle to Crossover Drive!

We'll be bioblitzing around the California Academy of Sciences, up at Stow Lake and Strawberry Hill, in the oak woodlands, and everywhere in between.

Bring your smartphone and/or a camera, your curiosity and tons of enthusiasm. We’ll rally some experts and folks who know the area. Together we’ll make some great discoveries, get to know these places and each other better!

A Bio-Blitz is an intensive one-day study of biodiversity in a specific location, bringing scientists and volunteer citizen-scientists together. Together, we’ll look for snails, birds, mammals, frogs, butterflies, other insects, spiders, trees, worms, flowers, and everything else we can find!

People of all ages and skill levels are welcome! Bring your smart phone for sure. Bonus: camera, binoculars, and magnifying glasses. We’ll enter observations in iNaturalist and join together at the end to find out how many observations we made and how many species we found. Past blitzes in Oakland, San Francisco, and San Mateo have averaged 1000 observations and 200+ species each. Hooray!

Don't have an iNat account yet? No problem!Sign up for an iNaturalist account, then download the app: iPhone, Android.

Brought to you by the California Academy of Sciences, Nerds for Nature, Nature in the City and iNaturalist.

The fun starts  at 9 AM Saturday at the back entrance of the Academy at 75 Nancy Pelosi Dr.  We will blitz for three hours and then meet up around noon to go over our finds!
results.title: Eastern Golden Gate Park BioBlitz

results.description:
This project is designed to document and identify the higher fungi (Basidiomycetes and Ascomycetes, excluding lichenized fungi) occuring in the California Floristic Province. 

Fungal fruitbodies tend to be ephemeral, and the documentation of fruiting locations is scarce compared with that of plants. Additionally, many areas of the CFP are poorly documented in terms of their fungal diversity. 

Share your observations, explore undocumented areas, record fruitbody locations, and help with identification of Dikarya fungi.
results.title: Fungi of the California Floristic Province

results.terms:
Observations posted to this project must fall into the superphylum Dikarya (Basidiomycetes and Ascomycetes, the higher fungi). Most macrofungi observable to the naked eye are within this group. 

Observations must occur within the California Floristic Province (CFP), which stretches from southern Oregon's Klamath Mountains to northern Baja California, Mexico and includes the southern Cascades, Coast Ranges, Sierra Nevada, Central Valley, Transverse Ranges, and Peninsular Ranges. See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/California_Floristic_Province for more information. 

To facilitate identification, detailed photos need to be included with each observation, including: an overall view of the fruitbody in situ, a view of the gills or fertile surface, and if possible a view of the stipe and substrate the fruitbody is growing from. Spore prints and/or dried specimens may be necessary to identify to species. Please know the legality of collecting in any location prior to doing so.

Under the Wild Animals Protection Ordinance (Cap 170), it is illegal to “hunt” any protected wild animal without a permit, where “animal” means any animal other than fish or marine invertebrate, and “hunt” means any act aimed at capture of an animal.

Any opinions, findings, conclusions or recommendations expressed in this material / event do not necessarily reflect the views of the Government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region.

results.description:
The new frontier of wildlife research: The ecology of the urban coyote. 

Los Angeles is the second most populous city in the country, and has been home to coyotes since its creation. We know now that there are some coyotes that spend their entire lives within the bounds of Los Angeles City. Beyond that, however, much of their ecology is shrouded in mystery.

The goal of this project through the Santa Monica Mountains National Park Service is to provide insight into the lives of coyotes living in Los Angeles, identify ways to minimize future human wildlife conflict in a humane and effective manner, and foster co-existence with urban wildlife.
results.title: LA Urban Coyote Project

results.description:
The main objective of the Milwaukee County Coyote Watch project is to learn more about coyote populations in Milwaukee County and monitor their behaviors! We ask that residents of Milwaukee County report any sightings of coyotes that they have to this new, easy-to-use, public database! 

Look closely! We will have several marked animals around targeted areas of Milwaukee County as well. Marked animals will have colored "ear tags". By identifying individual animals, we can tie observations and behaviors to specific animals and be proactive in responding to habituated animals. If you see a marked animal, please fill in the corresponding fields. This will help us get a better idea of when these animals are active and potentially interacting with people.

We are eager to see where coyotes are being seen around Milwaukee County and how they are behaving. Your observations will help natural resource managers and researchers understand the distribution and behavior of our urban coyotes!

Thank you for your help!
results.title: Milwaukee County Coyote Watch

Thank you for entering observations of mosquitoes in Hawai’i using iNaturalist! Hawaii is home to six invasive mosquito species. By adding observations to this project you will be helping document where and when these species are found across the islands. results.description:
The purpose of this project is make use of the wealth of wildlife observations collected by skilled trackers across North America and to develop an online community of track experts that will help validate track observations.

Mammals are often missing from citizen scientist efforts as they are very hard to detect in the wild. Currently mammals make up only 5% of the observations on iNaturalist! Birds have throngs of enthusiastic birders, reptiles and amphibians have dedicated herpers, but mammals historically lack a group of dedicated citizen advocates... until the wildlife trackers.

In the past decade there has been a resurgence in interest in animal tracking and since the establishment of the CyberTracker Tracker Certification system, competent trackers with tested and documented identification skills are appearing around the country.

Put your interest in tracking to use by submitting your observations to this project. They will make a real contribution to science and conservation.
results.title: North American Animal Tracking Database
results.terms:
Clear track photos must be submitted that are identifiable. Blurry or dark photos, photos taken from a far distance, or photos of very obscure tracks should not be submitted. Please include a scale in every photo if at all possible.

Please be cautious about how you identify your tracks, especially if you are identifying to the species level based on range. It is generally better to err on the side of caution and identify only to the genus or family level if there is doubt on the species. You can always include your thoughts in the notes.

While tracks from any taxa are appropriate, mammals, especially rare and difficult to observe species should generally be targeted. Please take care to obscure the location of any observations of rare or desirable species.

Because track identification can be very difficult, we encourage users to become certified through the CyberTracker Tracker Certification. This allows us to know the skill levels of those submitting observations and can enable researchers to focus on the most reliable observations.

Please make sure you have permission to submit observations if you are on private lands. Don't break any laws!

results.description: How many species occur in Vermont? You’d think we’d know this for a small state steeped in a rich tradition of naturalists. But, the simple answer is, no one really knows. Introducing the Vermont Atlas of Life project at iNaturalist. Help us discover, map and monitor life across Vermont. We do know how many species there are of some of the popular taxonomic groups like birds (385) and mammals (58). But how many invertebrates are there in Vermont? A back-of-the-envelope estimate puts the number at just over 21,400 species! There are about 2,150 species of vascular plants, with approximately 1,400 native plants. Not including protists, bacteria or viruses, we humans share Vermont with at least 26,000 to 45,000 species, although no one knows for sure just how many. The list continues to grow as we discover new native and introduced species across the state. For example, citizen naturalists helped the Vermont Butterfly Survey (2002-2007) discover 12 new butterflies in the state, in the process creating a conservation watch list based on our newfound knowledge. We don’t have to go far to discover new and surprising species. A new plant, never before described to science, was recently discovered in the Green Mountains. Join our growing community of citizen naturalists from around the Green Mountain State in discovering and sharing observations of Vermont life. Your observations can be turned into research-grade, citizen science data that will help us discover, track and ultimately conserve our natural heritage. Learn about our other atlas projects, news, and more at the Vermont Atlas of Life web site.
results.title: Vermont Atlas of Life
results.terms:
The Vermont Atlas of Life encourages responsible use of the iNaturalist platform. Please consider the following rules of etiquette when you are in the field:
•	don’t disturb species of conservation concern
•	be respectful of research sites and equipment
•	leave the habitat as you found it
•	do not trespass on private property without landowner permission
•	communicate with land owners and managers about your activities
•	don’t make public disclosure of sensitive species location information (see below)
•	be a model for ethical wildlife watching behavior. For more detailed guidelines, visit the American Birding Association's Code of Birding Ethics at http://www.aba.org/about/ethics.html.
•	appreciate and respect Vermont's biodiversity.

Please note that if you would like to obscure the location of a particular sighting you may select “Private” under the option for “Change Geoprivacy.” Private locations will not be visible on the public map, but will still be visible to project biologists and can be used for science and conservation purposes. 

This project only includes native or naturalized species. This includes invasive species and naturalized horticultural plants, but does not include those purposely planted in yards and gardens, pets or captive and escaped animals.

Thank you for joining the Vermont Atlas of Life. We appreciate your help collecting distribution information on Vermont biodiversity.

results.description: iSeahorse is a tool for seahorse science and conservation. You can upload your observations via this project page, or via www.iseahorse.org, our full-featured project website. iSeahorse harnesses the power of citizen scientists — anyone, anywhere in the world who sees a seahorse in the wild — to improve our understanding of these mysterious and beautiful and animal and protect them from overfishing and other threats. Anyone can join iSeahorse. Whether you’re a diver, or a fisher, or a scientist, or a seahorse enthusiast, you can upload your photos and observations to iSeahorse. You can help identifyseahorse species. You can advocate for their protection in your ocean neighbourhood. Scientists from Project Seahorse and seahorse experts around the world will use your observations to better understand seahorse behaviour, species ranges, and the threats seahorses face. We will use this knowledge to improve seahorse conservation across the globe. Thanks for joining our project!
